The function $f ( z ) = \frac { \sin ( z ) } { z ( 1 - z ) }$ has poles at $z = 0 , 1$ . The poles are simple and lie inside the given contour. We will use Residue Theorem to evaluate the integral. 

\begin{align*}
\text{Res} ( f , 0 ) &= \lim _{z \to 0 }  \frac { \sin ( z ) } { 1 - z }  =  \lim _{ z \to 0 }  \frac { \sin ( z ) } { 1 - 0 }  =  0  \\
\text { Res } ( f , 1 ) & =  \lim _{ z \to 1 }  \frac { \sin ( 1 ) ( z - 1 ) } { z ( 1 - z ) }  =  - \sin ( 1 ) 
\end{align*}

Summing these residues, we have:  \[ 0 + ( - \sin(1) ) = - \sin ( 1 ) \]

Thus, the integral is evaluated as $2 \pi i \times \left(- \sin ( 1 ) \right)$.

